# Mobile UI Implementation Rules

Use this rule when adding or updating mobile-optimized UI in the web application.

## Scope and Constraints

- Changes must **ONLY** affect mobile screen sizes. Use responsive breakpoints such as **≤768px** or the mobile breakpoint already used in the project.
- **DO NOT** modify any desktop UI layouts.
- **DO NOT** modify application logic, data flow, APIs, or component behavior.
- Changes must be **purely visual** and limited to responsive styling adjustments.

## Mobile UI Goals

### 1. Reduce visual density
- Decrease padding and margins within sections and containers.
- Make cards, panels, and sections thinner and more compact.

### 2. Resize UI elements for mobile
- Reduce the size of fonts, icons, buttons, calendar/date inputs, time inputs, and sliders.
- Ensure elements remain readable and accessible.

### 3. Improve vertical layout
- Convert multi-column layouts into single-column stacked layouts on mobile.
- Allow components to expand to full width where appropriate.

### 4. Add collapsible sections
- Allow sections, cards, or grouped controls to be collapsible/expandable to reduce scrolling.
- Default large or secondary sections to collapsed where appropriate.

### 5. Maintain touch usability
- Ensure interactive elements maintain adequate touch targets (**~44px** recommended).

## Implementation Guidelines

- Use responsive CSS or framework breakpoints (media queries, Tailwind responsive classes, etc.).
- Prefer responsive styling adjustments instead of duplicating components.
- Preserve the existing component structure and application logic.
- Maintain visual consistency with the current design system.

## Validation Requirements

- Desktop views must remain **visually identical** to the current version.
- Verify usability on common mobile widths (**320px–430px**).
- Confirm that **no functionality or JavaScript logic** has changed.
